    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA130-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu piriviṭai (G1+2: pirivuṭaimai) melinta talaivi vaṉpoṟai (ER, ET: vaṉpuṟai) etiraḻintu colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE who has weakened in the time separation said in desolation in the face of being comforted.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA130">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            vaṭuviṉṟu niṟainta māṉṟērt teṇkaṇ</l>
<l>            maṭivāyt taṇṇumai naṭuva ṇārppak</l>
<l>            kōli ṉeṟintu kālait tōṉṟiya</l>
<l>            cennīrp potuviṉaic cemmaṉ mūtūrt</l>
<l>            tamatucey vāḻkkaiyi ṉiṉiya tuṇṭō </l>
<l>            veṉaivirup puṭaiya rāyiṉu niṉaivilar</l>
<l>            nērnta neñcu nekiḻnta tōḷum</l>
<l>            vāṭiya variyu nōkki nīṭā</l>
<l>            tevaṉcey taṉaḷip pēraña ruṟuviyeṉ</l>
<l>            ṟorunāḷ kūṟiṉṟu milarē virinīr </l>
<l>            vaiyaka varaiyaḷa viṟanta</l>
<l>            vevva nōypiṟi tuyavuttuṇai yiṉṟē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Is there anything as pleasing as a living made by oneself(?)<note place="foot">Here <term xml:lang="ta">tamatu</term> certainly must be read as a genitive, but this is awkward in the actual construction (<term xml:lang="ta">cey</term> seems to demand an instrumental). It is tempting to change the word order: "one's living, made in..."</note></l>
<l rend="indent">in this excellent old village with public work of an upright kind<note place="foot">What are the sociological implications of this description?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">that befalls in the morning, the clear-eyed leather-mouthed</l>
<l rend="indent3">Taṇṇumai drum being beaten by the stick,</l>
<l rend="indent4">so that [its] central part roars,</l>
<l rend="indent2">to the chariot [drawn by] horses, contented,</l>
<l rend="indent4">as they were without reproach?<note place="foot">That part is missing even in K.P.; it is difficult to see the relation between line 1 and what follows, since <term xml:lang="ta">Taṇṇumai</term> drums are not expected to be beaten on chariots, and anyway the relation is not marked morphologically.</note></l>
<l>However much longing he may possess, he doesn't think,</l>
<l>he is not one to talk<note place="foot">For the type of negation where the perfective neuter singular in -<term xml:lang="ta">aṉṟu</term> has to be analysed as an verbal noun see note on NA 27.</note> even of a single day,</l>
<l rend="indent">looking at [her] heart that consented</l>
<l rend="indent">and [her] shoulder that is emaciated</l>
<l rend="indent">and [her] lines which have faded, not prolonging:</l>
<l rend="indent3">“what has she done, she who has this big grief?”</l>
<l>There is no companion in suffering other than troubled pain</l>
<l rend="indent">that has gone beyond the limit of the world of expanding waters.</l>
        </lg>
